# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: geographic-coordinate-system
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/100th-meridian-west] The **meridian 100° west** of the Prime Meridian of Greenwich is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, North America, the Pacific Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/100th-meridian-west] The 100th meridian west forms a great circle with the 80th meridian east.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/100th-meridian-west] In the United States, this meridian roughly marks the boundary between the semi-arid climate in the west and the humid continental and humid subtropical climates in the east, and as such roughly connotes the regions of the Eastern and the Western United States.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/100th-meridian-west] In the United States the meridian 100° west of Greenwich forms the eastern border of the Texas panhandle with Oklahoma (which traces its origin to the Adams-Onís Treaty in 1819 which settled the border between New Spain and the United States between the Red River and Arkansas River).
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/100th-meridian-west] Dodge City, Kansas lies exactly at the intersection of the Arkansas River and the 100th meridian.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/100th-meridian-west] As first noted by John Wesley Powell in the 1870s, there is a big difference in rainfall by the different sides of the meridian.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/100th-meridian-west] West of the meridian, raising livestock is much more economically important than east of it, and what agriculture does exist relies heavily on irrigation.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/100th-meridian-west] Historically, the meridian has often been taken as a rough boundary between the eastern and western United States.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/100th-meridian-west] White settlement, spreading westward after the American Civil War, settled the area around this meridian during the 1870s.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/100th-meridian-west] Highway 30 in Cozad, Nebraska, marks the place where the 100th meridian intersects with the routes of the Oregon Trail, Pony Express, transcontinental railroad, and the Lincoln Highway.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/105th-meridian-west] The **meridian 105° west of Greenwich** is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, North America, the Pacific Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/105th-meridian-west] The 105th meridian west forms a great circle with the 75th meridian east.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/105th-meridian-west] It serves as the reference meridian for the seventh time zone west of Greenwich, known as UTC-07 or the Mountain Time Zone in North America.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/105th-meridian-west] In the United States, Interstate Highway I-25 roughly parallels the meridian from Douglas, Wyoming to Las Vegas, New Mexico, and from Wellington, Colorado to the Prospect Road interchange (in Fort Collins, Colorado), I-25 happens to be almost exactly aligned along the 105th meridian west.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/105th-meridian-west] The meridian bisects Denver, Colorado, passing through Denver Union Station.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/105th-meridian-west] Throughout the Denver metro area, Kalamath Street is the road that most closely corresponds to the 105th meridian.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-meridian-east] The **meridian 10° east of Greenwich** is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, Europe, Africa, the Atlantic Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-meridian-east] The 10th meridian east forms a great circle with the 170th meridian west.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-meridian-east] In some world maps, the 10th Meridian East is used the centre (instead of Greenwich), to avoid cutting off the tip of Asia.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-meridian-west] The **meridian 10° west of Greenwich** is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, the Atlantic Ocean, Ireland, Africa, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-meridian-west] The 10th meridian west forms a great circle with the 170th meridian east.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-meridian-west] This longitude is the eastern limit of the Atlântico Brasileiro, Montevideo, Ezeiza and Comodoro Rivadavia flight information regions, as well as the western limit of the Luanda and Johannesburg Oceanic FIRs.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-meridian-west] The meridian defines the western limit of the New Swabia area in Queen Maud Land, Antarctica.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] The **6th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 6 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] It crosses Africa, the Indian Ocean, Southeast Asia, the Pacific Ocean, South America, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] Damage from the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami was concentrated at this latitude.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] The **7th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 7 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] It crosses Africa, the Indian Ocean, South Asia, Southeast Asia, the Pacific Ocean, South America, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] The **8th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 8 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] It crosses Africa, the Indian Ocean, South Asia, Southeast Asia, the Pacific Ocean, Central America, South America, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] The parallel defines part of the border between Somalia and Ethiopia.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] The Eight Degree Channel (Maliku Kandu) in the Indian Ocean is named after the parallel.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] The **9th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 9 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] The **10th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 10 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] It crosses Africa, the Indian Ocean, the Indian subcontinent, Southeast Asia, the Pacific Ocean, Central America, South America, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 12 hours, 43 minutes during the summer solstice and 11 hours, 33 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] On 21 June, the maximum altitude of the sun is 103.44 degrees and 56.56 degrees on 21 December.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] In this case an angle larger than 90° means that the culmination takes place at a maximum altitude of 76.56 degrees in the opposite cardinal direction.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] In the northern torrid zone, the Sun remains in the south during winter, but can reach over the zenith to the north in midsummer.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] A section of the border between Guinea and Sierra Leone is defined by the parallel.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] The Ten Degree Channel in the Indian Ocean is named after the parallel.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-north] In the end of part two of the Spanish television heist crime drama series *La casa de papel*, a point near Palawan island, Philippines, with the coordinates of 10th parallel north and 118,5º, was the meeting point of *El Professor* and *Raquel* one year after the heist.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-south] The **6th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 6 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-south] It crosses the Atlantic Ocean, Africa, the Indian Ocean, Southeast Asia, Australasia, the Pacific Ocean and South America.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-south] The **7th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 7 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-south] Part of the border between the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Angola is defined by the parallel.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-south] It is the most populous parallel south of the Equator, being home to between 86.1 million and 99.8 million people as of 2019.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-south] The **8th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 8 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-south] Two sections of the border between the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Angola are defined by the parallel.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-south] It passes through 10 out of the 26 states of Brazil.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-south] The **9th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 9 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-south] It crosses the Atlantic Ocean, Africa, the Indian Ocean, Australasia, the Pacific Ocean and South America.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-south] The parallel passes through 11 out of the 26 states of Brazil.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-south] The **10th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 10 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/10th-parallel-south] Part of the border between Brazil and Peru is defined by the parallel.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/110th-meridian-west] The **meridian 110° west of Greenwich** is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, North America, the Pacific Ocean, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/110th-meridian-west] The 110th meridian west forms a great circle with the 70th meridian east.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/110th-meridian-west] In Canada, the meridian forms the boundary between Nunavut and the Northwest Territories north of the parallel 70° north.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/110th-meridian-west] Originally 110°W was intended as the Fourth Meridian for the Dominion Land Survey, but because of the imperfect surveying methods of the time, the meridian was placed a few hundred metres west of this longitude.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/110th-meridian-west] The Fourth Meridian has been the entire boundary between Alberta and Saskatchewan since 1905.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/110th-meridian-west] In the United States, the meridian formed the western border of the historic and extralegal Territory of Jefferson.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] A **geographic coordinate system** (**GCS**) is a spherical or geodetic coordinate system for measuring and communicating positions directly on Earth as latitude and longitude.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] It is the simplest, oldest, and most widely used type of the various spatial reference systems that are in use, and forms the basis for most others.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Although latitude and longitude form a coordinate tuple like a Cartesian coordinate system, geographic coordinate systems are not Cartesian because the measurements are angles and are not on a planar surface.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] A full GCS specification, such as those listed in the EPSG and ISO 19111 standards, also includes a choice of geodetic datum (including an Earth ellipsoid), as different datums will yield different latitude and longitude values for the same location.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The invention of a geographic coordinate system is generally credited to Eratosthenes of Cyrene, who composed his now-lost *Geography* at the Library of Alexandria in the 3rd century BC.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] A century later, Hipparchus of Nicaea improved on this system by determining latitude from stellar measurements rather than solar altitude and determining longitude by timings of lunar eclipses, rather than dead reckoning.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy credited him with the full adoption of longitude and latitude, rather than measuring latitude in terms of the length of the midsummer day.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy's 2nd-century *Geography* used the same prime meridian but measured latitude from the Equator instead.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] After their work was translated into Arabic in the 9th century, Al-Khwārizmī's *Book of the Description of the Earth* corrected Marinus' and Ptolemy's errors regarding the length of the Mediterranean Sea, causing medieval Arabic cartography to use a prime meridian around 10° east of Ptolemy's line.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Mathematical cartography resumed in Europe following Maximus Planudes' recovery of Ptolemy's text a little before 1300; the text was translated into Latin at Florence by Jacopo d'Angelo around 1407.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] In 1884, the United States hosted the International Meridian Conference, attended by representatives from twenty-five nations.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Twenty-two of them agreed to adopt the longitude of the Royal Observatory in Greenwich, England as the zero-reference line.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The Dominican Republic voted against the motion, while France and Brazil abstained.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] France adopted Greenwich Mean Time in place of local determinations by the Paris Observatory in 1911.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The *latitude* φ of a point on Earth's surface is defined in one of three ways, depending on the type of coordinate system.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] In each case, the latitude is the angle formed by the plane of the equator and a line formed by the point on the surface and a second point on equatorial plane.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The path that joins all points of the same latitude traces a circle on the surface of Earth, as viewed from above the north or south pole, called parallels, as they are parallel to the equator and to each other.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The north pole is 90° N; the south pole is 90° S.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The 0° parallel of latitude is defined to be the equator, the fundamental plane of a geographic coordinate system.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The equator divides the globe into Northern and Southern Hemispheres.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The *longitude* λ of a point on Earth's surface is the angle east or west of a reference meridian to another meridian that passes through that point.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] All meridians are halves of great ellipses, which converge at the North and South Poles.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The meridian of the British Royal Observatory in Greenwich, in southeast London, England, is the international prime meridian, although some organizations—such as the French Institut national de l'information géographique et forestière—continue to use other meridians for internal purposes.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The antipodal meridian of Greenwich is both 180°W and 180°E.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] This is not to be conflated with the International Date Line, which partly overlaps with the 180° meridian but diverges from it in several places for political and convenience reasons, including between far eastern Russia and the far western Aleutian Islands.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The combination of these two components specifies the position of any location on the surface of Earth, without consideration of altitude or depth.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The visual grid on a map formed by lines of latitude and longitude is known as a *graticule*.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The origin/zero point of this system is located in the Gulf of Guinea about 625 km (390 mi) south of Tema, Ghana, a location often facetiously called Null Island.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] In order to use the theoretical definitions of latitude, longitude, and height to precisely measure actual locations on the physical earth, a *geodetic datum* must be used.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] A *horizonal datum* is used to precisely measure latitude and longitude, while a *vertical datum* is used to measure elevation or altitude.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Both types of datum bind a mathematical model of the shape of the earth (usually a reference ellipsoid for a horizontal datum, and a more precise geoid for a vertical datum) to the earth.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Traditionally, this binding was created by a network of control points, surveyed locations at which monuments are installed, and were only accurate for a region of the surface of the Earth.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Newer datums are based on a global network for satellite measurements (GNSS, VLBI, SLR and DORIS).
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] This combination of a mathematical model and physical binding ensures that users of the same datum obtain identical coordinates for a given physical point.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] However, different datums typically produce different coordinates for the same location (sometimes deviating several hundred meters) not due to actual movement, but because the reference system itself is shifted.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Because any spatial reference system or map projection is ultimately calculated from latitude and longitude, it is crucial that they clearly state the datum on which they are based.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] For example, a UTM coordinate based on a WGS84 realisation will be different than a UTM coordinate based on NAD27 for the same location.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Transforming coordinates from one datum to another requires a datum transformation method such as a Helmert transformation, although in certain situations a simple translation may be sufficient.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums may be global, meaning that they represent the whole Earth, or they may be regional, meaning that they represent an ellipsoid best-fit to only a portion of the Earth.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums with a regional fit of the ellipsoid that are chosen by a national cartographical organization include the North American Datums, the European ED50, and the British OSGB36.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Given a location, the datum provides the latitude $\phi$ and longitude $\lambda$ .
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] In the United Kingdom there are three common latitude, longitude, and height systems in use.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] WGS 84 differs at Greenwich from the one used on published maps OSGB36 by approximately 112 m.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Points on the Earth's surface move relative to each other due to continental plate motion, subsidence, and diurnal Earth tidal movement caused by the Moon and the Sun.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] This daily movement can be as much as a meter.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Continental movement can be up to 10 cm a year, or 10 m in a century.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] A weather system high-pressure area can cause a sinking of 5 mm.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Scandinavia is rising by 1 cm a year as a result of the melting of the ice sheets of the last ice age, but neighboring Scotland is rising by only 0.2 cm.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] These changes are insignificant if a regional datum is used, but are statistically significant if a global datum is used.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] On the GRS 80 or WGS 84 spheroid at sea level at the Equator, one latitudinal second measures 30.715 m, one latitudinal minute is 1843 m and one latitudinal degree is 110.6 km.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The circles of longitude, meridians, meet at the geographical poles, with the west–east width of a second naturally decreasing as latitude increases.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] On the Equator at sea level, one longitudinal second measures 30.92 m, a longitudinal minute is 1855 m and a longitudinal degree is 111.3 km.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The returned measure of meters per degree latitude varies continuously with latitude.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] The formulae both return units of meters per degree.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] ( $\textstyle {\beta }\,\!$ is known as the reduced (or parametric) latitude).
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Aside from rounding, this is the exact distance along a parallel of latitude; getting the distance along the shortest route will be more work, but those two distances are always within 0.6 m of each other if the two points are one degree of longitude apart.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] Like any series of multiple-digit numbers, latitude-longitude pairs can be challenging to communicate and remember.
[src:geographic-coordinate-system/geographic-coordinate-system] These are not distinct coordinate systems, only alternative methods for expressing latitude and longitude measurements.
